    "id": 169,
    "title": "Stuffed Quesadillas",
    "category": "cooking",
    "emoji": "🫓",
    "ages": "4-12",
    "time": "20 min",
    "difficulty": "easy",
    "supplies": [
      "Large flour tortillas",
      "Shredded cheese",
      "Fillings of choice: beans, corn, capsicum, chicken, spinach",
      "Butter or oil",
      "Frying pan",
      "Sour cream and salsa to serve"
    ],
    "description": "Layer cheese and fillings between tortillas and pan-fry until crispy and melty.",
    "steps": [
      "Plan the filling: choose 3-4 ingredients maximum. Good combinations: cheese with chicken and corn; cheese with black beans and avocado; cheese with leftover beef and capsicum. More than 4 fillings makes flipping messy.",
      "Prepare all fillings before cooking: pre-cook any raw meat completely. Slice vegetables thinly so they heat through in the 2-3 minutes available. Grate the cheese - it melts more evenly than chunks.",
      "Heat a large flat pan over medium heat: no oil needed - the tortilla toasts directly on the dry pan. Medium heat prevents burning the outside before the cheese inside melts.",
      "Lay the tortilla flat in the pan: it should roughly match the pan diameter and will begin to warm and slightly puff immediately.",
      "Sprinkle cheese over one half of the tortilla: use enough to cover the half-moon fully. The cheese is structural - it melts and binds all other fillings together. Skimp on cheese and the quesadilla falls apart.",
      "Add fillings on top of the cheese on the same half: spread evenly. Leave a 1cm border at the straight edge so nothing spills when folded.",
      "Fold the empty half over to make a half-moon: fold gently but decisively. Press down lightly with a spatula to help the halves adhere.",
      "Cook for 2-3 minutes until the underside is golden: peek underneath with the spatula. Golden brown is correct. If it darkens in under 90 seconds, the heat is too high.",
      "Flip in one confident motion: slide the spatula fully under the half-moon before lifting. A decisive flip is far better than a tentative one - hesitation causes the filling to shift and spill.",
      "Cook the second side for 2 minutes: press down lightly for full contact with the pan. Both sides should be an even golden colour.",
      "Slide out and rest for 1 minute before cutting: cutting immediately causes molten cheese to flow out. One minute of resting allows the cheese to partly reset. Cut into 3 wedges.",
      "Serve with dipping accompaniments: sour cream, tomato salsa, and guacamole are classic. Set out small dishes and let children build their own dipping selection."
    ],
    "tips": "Don't overfill or they will burst when flipped. Cheese on both sides of the filling acts as glue to hold everything together."
