    "id": 173,
    "title": "Vegetable Soup from Scratch",
    "category": "cooking",
    "emoji": "🍲",
    "ages": "4-12",
    "time": "45 min",
    "difficulty": "easy",
    "supplies": [
      "2 carrots",
      "2 celery stalks",
      "1 onion",
      "2 potatoes",
      "1 zucchini",
      "1 litre vegetable stock",
      "1 can diced tomatoes",
      "Olive oil",
      "Salt, pepper, dried herbs",
      "Large pot"
    ],
    "description": "Chop vegetables together and simmer into a hearty soup - a genuine meal cooked from scratch.",
    "steps": [
      "Choose the vegetables together: let children pick 2 vegetables that will be their personal contribution. Good picks: corn kernels, peas, green beans, leek, sweet potato. Ownership over ingredient choice dramatically increases willingness to eat the final soup.",
      "Peel and chop all vegetables into bite-sized pieces: children can safely chop soft vegetables like zucchini and mushrooms with a rounded table knife on a stable board. Cut root vegetables yourself.",
      "Heat olive oil in a large pot over medium heat: the oil should shimmer but not smoke. A heavy-bottomed pot prevents vegetables from catching on the base.",
      "Add onion and cook for 3-4 minutes until soft: stir every minute. Softened onions release sweetness and become the flavour base for the whole soup.",
      "Add carrots and celery and cook for another 3 minutes: these harder vegetables need a head start before softer ones are added. Keep the heat at medium and stir occasionally.",
      "Add potatoes, zucchini, diced tomatoes, and stock: pour in enough stock to cover all vegetables by 2-3cm. Tomatoes add acidity that balances the sweetness of the carrots and onion.",
      "Add salt, pepper, and dried herbs: thyme, parsley, or mixed Italian herbs all work well. A bay leaf adds depth.",
      "Bring to a boil, then reduce heat and simmer for 20 minutes: a simmer means small occasional bubbles, not a rolling boil. Cover with a lid slightly ajar.",
      "Test vegetables for tenderness: pierce a potato cube with a knife. If it slides off the knife easily, the soup is ready. If it resists, simmer for 5 more minutes.",
      "Taste and adjust seasoning: taste with a clean spoon. Add more salt if flat, a squeeze of lemon juice if it needs brightness, more herbs if it tastes thin.",
      "Add pasta or legumes for a heartier soup (optional): stir in a handful of small pasta or a drained can of white beans in the last 10 minutes. This turns a light broth into a filling meal.",
      "Serve with crusty bread: leftover soup thickens overnight in the fridge and often tastes even better the next day. Reheat gently and add a splash of water if too thick."
    ],
    "tips": "Let kids choose two vegetables to add that are their own contribution. They are far more likely to eat soup they helped make."
