    "id": 203,
    "title": "Build a Periscope",
    "category": "science",
    "emoji": "🔭",
    "ages": "7-12",
    "time": "45 min",
    "difficulty": "medium",
    "supplies": [
      "Two small milk cartons",
      "Two small mirrors",
      "Scissors",
      "Tape",
      "A ruler and pencil"
    ],
    "description": "Build a working periscope from cardboard and mirrors to see around corners and over obstacles.",
    "steps": [
      "Understand how a periscope works: two mirrors at 45-degree angles facing each other redirect light around a corner. Light enters the top, bounces down to the bottom mirror, and exits toward the viewer's eye.",
      "Gather materials: two tall cardboard milk or juice cartons (1-litre size), strong tape, a craft knife (adult use), and two small mirrors approximately 8x8cm. Compact mirrors or mirror tile pieces work well.",
      "Rinse and dry both cartons. Cut the folded tops off both to create two open-ended rectangular tubes.",
      "Tape the two cartons end-to-end with strong tape to make one long tube: align them carefully so the seam is tight. The combined height should be approximately 40cm.",
      "Cut the viewing openings: at the bottom of the combined tube, cut a rectangular opening on one face. At the top, cut a matching opening on the opposite face.",
      "Set the 45-degree angle: fold a square piece of paper diagonally in half to create a 45-degree guide triangle. Use this to position each mirror at the correct angle inside the tube.",
      "Attach the bottom mirror: tape the mirror inside the bottom of the tube at 45 degrees, angled so it faces upward toward the top opening.",
      "Attach the top mirror: tape the mirror inside the top of the tube at 45 degrees, angled so it faces downward toward the bottom opening. The two mirror faces must point toward each other.",
      "Test it: look through the bottom opening. You should see what is in front of the top opening. If the image appears incorrect, check that both mirrors face each other at matching angles.",
      "Decorate the periscope: paint or cover with coloured paper. Add a submarine design, camouflage pattern, or spy-themed markings.",
      "Use it in different situations: look over a fence, around a wall corner, under a sofa, or through a small gap. This is the same device submarines use to see above water while submerged.",
      "Discuss the physics: light travels in straight lines. Mirrors change direction by reflecting light. Two mirrors at complementary angles redirect light around a corner. This principle also applies in binoculars, cameras, and telescopes."
    ],
    "tips": "The 45-degree mirror angle is critical. Fold a square piece of paper diagonally in half to use as a guide for setting the angle."
