    "id": 211,
    "title": "Flour Tortillas from Scratch",
    "category": "cooking",
    "emoji": "🫓",
    "ages": "5–12",
    "time": "40 min",
    "difficulty": "easy",
    "supplies": [
      "3 cups all-purpose flour",
      "1½ tsp fine salt",
      "1 tsp baking powder",
      "⅓ cup lard, butter, or vegetable shortening",
      "1 cup hot (not boiling) water",
      "Rolling pin",
      "Cast iron skillet or heavy pan"
    ],
    "description": "An authentic Mexican staple that kids can make almost entirely themselves. Kneading, resting, rolling - it's hands-on at every step. A gateway into how fats and gluten interact in dough.",
    "steps": [
      "Explain what a tortilla is: a thin unleavened flatbread that is one of the oldest foods in the Americas, eaten daily in Mexico and Central America. Making them from scratch takes about 30 minutes and the result is incomparably better than packaged versions.",
      "Gather ingredients: 2 cups plain flour, 1 teaspoon salt, half a teaspoon baking powder, 3 tablespoons lard or butter, and about three-quarters of a cup of hot (not boiling) water.",
      "Whisk flour, salt, and baking powder together in a large bowl: dry-mixing first ensures even distribution of the leavening and salt.",
      "Add the fat and rub it in with your fingers: work the fat into the flour until no lumps remain and the mixture resembles coarse sand. This is the same technique used in pastry making.",
      "Add hot water gradually: pour in a little at a time, mixing with a fork and then your hands. Stop adding water when the dough just comes together. It should not be sticky.",
      "Knead briefly on a floured surface for 1-2 minutes until smooth: unlike bread dough, tortilla dough needs only minimal kneading - just enough to make it smooth and uniform.",
      "Cover with a kitchen towel and rest for 10 minutes: this is the most important step. Resting lets the gluten relax so the dough stretches without springing back. Do not skip it.",
      "Divide into 12 equal balls: use a scale for uniformity, or eyeball 12 portions. Roll each into a smooth ball.",
      "Roll each ball very thin on a floured surface: aim for 2-3mm thickness and roughly circular shape. If the dough springs back, let it rest 2 more minutes and try again.",
      "Heat a dry (no oil) cast iron or heavy skillet on medium-high: the skillet must be hot before the first tortilla goes in.",
      "Cook each tortilla for 30-60 seconds per side: small dark spots appear when it is ready to flip. The tortilla may puff up slightly - this is normal and desirable.",
      "Stack cooked tortillas under a clean towel: the steam from the stack keeps them pliable and warm. Eat within 30 minutes or cool completely and store in an airtight bag for up to 3 days."
    ],
    "tips": "The rest step is critical - don't skip it or the dough will spring back when you try to roll it. Lard gives the most authentic flavour, but butter works well too."
