    "id": 213,
    "title": "Fresh Pasta Dough",
    "category": "cooking",
    "emoji": "🍝",
    "ages": "6–12",
    "time": "1 hr",
    "difficulty": "medium",
    "supplies": [
      "2 cups (260g) '00' flour or plain all-purpose flour",
      "3 large eggs (about 170g)",
      "1 tsp olive oil",
      "Pinch of salt",
      "Rolling pin or pasta machine",
      "Large pot for cooking",
      "Semolina or extra flour for dusting"
    ],
    "description": "Making pasta from scratch connects kids to Italian culinary tradition and demonstrates gluten development in a way no other recipe can. The dough starts crumbly, then becomes silky smooth with kneading - a tangible lesson in food science.",
    "steps": [
      "Explain fresh pasta: unlike dried pasta from a box, fresh pasta is made from only flour and eggs with no water. The result is silky, tender noodles that cook in 2 minutes. It is one of the most satisfying things to make from scratch.",
      "Gather ingredients: 200g of 00 flour or plain flour (per 2 people), 2 large eggs, half a teaspoon of salt, and 1 teaspoon of olive oil. Have a pasta machine or rolling pin ready.",
      "Mound the flour on a clean bench or in a large bowl and make a well in the centre: the well should be wide enough to hold the eggs without them spilling over the edge.",
      "Crack eggs into the well, add oil and salt: use a fork to beat the eggs in the well, then begin incorporating flour from the inner walls gradually. Work slowly - if the wall of flour breaks, eggs will spill out.",
      "When too thick for a fork, use your hands to bring the dough together: press firmly to incorporate all the flour. The dough will look rough and crumbly at first - keep pressing.",
      "Knead for 8-10 minutes until smooth and silky: press the heel of your hand into the dough, fold, turn, and repeat. Set a timer. The dough transforms from sticky-rough to smooth-elastic as the gluten develops.",
      "The poke test: press a finger into the dough. It should spring back slowly. If it springs back immediately, knead 2 more minutes. This spring is the gluten network you just built.",
      "Wrap in cling film and rest at room temperature for 30 minutes: resting lets the gluten relax, making rolling much easier. Do not skip this step.",
      "Divide into 4 pieces: work with one piece at a time, keeping others wrapped. Roll very thin (1-2mm) using a rolling pin and lots of flour, or use a pasta machine starting at the widest setting and working down.",
      "Cut into fettuccine-width strips: dust the rolled sheet with semolina or flour, fold loosely, and slice across to make strips. Immediately unroll and toss to separate.",
      "Cook in well-salted boiling water for just 2-3 minutes: fresh pasta cooks far faster than dried. Taste after 2 minutes - it should be tender with just a hint of bite.",
      "Serve immediately with a simple sauce: butter and parmesan is the classic pairing that lets the fresh pasta shine. Ask children to compare the taste and texture to packaged dried pasta."
    ],
    "tips": "Kids often give up on the kneading - set a timer for 8 minutes and encourage them to keep going. The transformation from rough crumble to silky dough is remarkable and well worth the effort."
