    "id": 214,
    "title": "Korean Mung Bean Pancakes (Bindaetteok)",
    "category": "cooking",
    "emoji": "🥞",
    "ages": "7–12",
    "time": "45 min",
    "difficulty": "medium",
    "supplies": [
      "1 cup dried split mung beans (soak overnight)",
      "½ cup water",
      "1 tsp salt",
      "½ cup bean sprouts",
      "2 spring onions, sliced",
      "½ cup kimchi, chopped (optional)",
      "Vegetable oil for frying",
      "Blender",
      "Dipping sauce: 2 tbsp soy sauce + 1 tbsp rice vinegar + ½ tsp sesame oil"
    ],
    "description": "A beloved Korean street food that happens to be completely gluten-free. Soaked mung beans are blended into a thick batter. Kids learn about legumes, fermentation (if using kimchi), and Korean culinary culture while making something genuinely delicious.",
    "steps": [
      "Introduce bindaetteok: these Korean mung bean pancakes have been eaten for over 600 years and are a popular street food. The name comes from the word for mung bean. They are crispy on the outside, tender inside, and packed with vegetables.",
      "Soak dried mung beans: rinse the beans and soak in cold water for at least 4 hours, or overnight. The beans absorb water and soften significantly. Drain before using.",
      "Blend soaked beans: place drained beans in a blender with a small amount of water (just enough to help it blend) and salt. Blend until a thick, slightly coarse batter forms. Do not over-blend to a smooth paste - some texture is desirable.",
      "Check batter consistency: the batter should be as thick as hummus. If it pours off a spoon in a thin ribbon, it is too thin and the pancakes will fall apart. Add more blended beans or reduce water next time.",
      "Prepare the vegetables: rinse and dry bean sprouts, slice spring onions into thin rounds, and roughly chop kimchi if using. These can all be varied based on preference.",
      "Stir vegetables into the batter: fold in bean sprouts, spring onions, and kimchi. The vegetables add texture, flavour, and nutrition to every pancake.",
      "Make the dipping sauce: combine soy sauce, rice vinegar, a few drops of sesame oil, and a pinch of chilli flakes. Stir and taste. Adjust proportions to preference.",
      "Heat 2 tablespoons of oil in a frying pan over medium-high heat: the oil should be hot and shimmering before the batter goes in. Too little oil or not hot enough makes them stick and cook unevenly.",
      "Pour batter in rounds about 8cm wide: use a large spoon or ladle. Press each round flat with a spatula immediately after pouring.",
      "Cook for 3-4 minutes without moving: resist the urge to press or check. The pancake is ready to flip when the edges look dry and the underside is deep golden.",
      "Flip and cook a further 2-3 minutes: the second side cooks faster. Press down gently with the spatula. Both sides should be an even golden brown.",
      "Serve immediately with dipping sauce: bindaetteok is best eaten fresh and hot when the exterior is at maximum crispness. Discuss the history and cultural context of the dish over the meal."
    ],
    "tips": "The batter should be thick - like hummus. If it is too runny the pancakes fall apart. The longer you soak the beans, the easier they blend."
