    "title": "Back to School Pencil Case Decorating",
    "category": "seasonal",
    "emoji": "✏️",
    "ages": "4-12",
    "time": "30 min",
    "difficulty": "easy",
    "supplies": [
      "A plain canvas pencil case or fabric bag",
      "Fabric markers or fabric paint",
      "Washi tape (for temporary designs to guide painting)",
      "Iron (to set fabric marker, adult use)"
    ],
    "description": "Personalise a plain pencil case with fabric markers so it is completely one-of-a-kind for the new school year.",
    "steps": [
      "Introduce the activity: a personalised pencil case made with fabric markers is unique and permanent. Unlike stick-on decorations that fall off, fabric marker designs bond with the fabric and survive washing, making this a practical and meaningful back-to-school project.",
      "Gather materials: a plain canvas pencil case (available from craft stores or online, typically sold specifically for decorating), fabric markers or fabric paint, a piece of card to insert inside, and an iron for setting (adult use).",
      "Prepare the case: insert a piece of card inside the pencil case. This prevents paint or marker bleeding through to the back panel and gives a firm surface to draw on.",
      "Brainstorm the design: spend 5 minutes thinking about what to put on it. Options include the child's name in large decorative letters, a favourite animal, a character, a pattern (stars, spots, stripes), a scene, or a combination.",
      "Sketch first: lightly draw the design with a regular pencil on scrap paper first to plan the layout. Where will the name go? What size should each element be? Adjust before committing.",
      "Transfer to the case: draw the design outline lightly on the pencil case with a light-coloured fabric marker or very light pencil marks that will be covered by colour.",
      "Add colour: fill in the design with fabric markers, working from background elements to foreground elements. Let each colour dry slightly (2-3 minutes) before adding adjacent colours to avoid bleeding.",
      "Add outlines and details: once the main colours are dry, add a dark outline around shapes to make them pop. Add small details like dots, patterns inside shapes, and shading.",
      "Write the name: if including the child's name, use a thick fabric marker for the letters. Block letters filled with a second colour look particularly strong.",
      "Let dry fully: allow at least 1 hour for all the fabric marker ink to dry completely. Do not close the case while drying or the panels will stick together.",
      "Heat-set the design: an adult places the case face down on an ironing board. Iron the reverse side for 3-4 minutes using a medium-hot setting (cotton/linen). This heat-sets the pigments and makes the design washable.",
      "Fill with new stationery and celebrate the finished work: the pencil case is now a piece of the child's own design heading to school every day."
    ],
    "tips": "Fabric markers from a craft store are much more vibrant and wash-proof than regular markers. This also works on plain tote bags, caps, and t-shirts."
